(), there's no question about that.<br /><br />We do locks_remove_file() independently on -&gt;release, but yes, it's<br />basically done just before the last release.<br /><br />But it has the *exact* same semantics as release, including very much<br />having nothing what-so-ever to do with "last close()".<br /><br />If the file descriptor is opened for other reasons (ie mmap, /proc<br />accesses, whatever), then that delays locks_remove_file() the same way<br />it delays release.<br /><br />None of that has *anothing* to do with "synchronous". Thinking it does is wrong.<br /><br />And none of this has *anything* to do with the issue that Maxim<br />pointed to in the mailing list web page, which was about write caches,<br />and how you cannot (and MUST NOT) delay them until release time.<br /><br />            Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
